рдЗрдВрдЯрд░рдиреЗрдЯ рдкрд░ 10 рд╕рд╛рд▓ рдХреА рдПрдХ рд▓рдбрд╝рдХреА рдмрдирдХрд░ рд╡реЗрдмрдХреИрдо рдХреЗ рд╕рд╛рдордиреЗ рдпреМрдирдХреНрд░рд┐рдпрд╛ рдХрд░рдиреЗ рдХреЗ рд▓рд┐рдП рдСрдирд▓рд╛рдЗрди рд╕рдВрдкрд░реНрдХ рдХрд░рдиреЗ рд╡рд╛рд▓реЗ 110 рдмреНрд░рд┐рддрд╛рдиреА рдирд╛рдЧрд░рд┐рдХреЛрдВ рдХреЗ рд░реВрдк рдореЗрдВ рдмрджрдирд╛рдо рдХрд┐рдП рдЬрд╛рдиреЗ рд╡рд╛рд▓реЗ рдПрдХ 41 рд╡рд░реНрд╖реАрдп рдЖрддрд┐рдВ India's apex river Ganga on Tuesday swelled to the danger levels at many places in Uttar Pradesh and is constantly rising up it's banks with administrative authorities in the national capital also keeping a very close eye on the water level. With the release of 20,000 cusecs of water from Haridwar, the river is inundating the areas in Bijnore, Muzaffarnagar, Meerut, Ghaziabad, Bulandshahar and Aligarh in UP. Water of ganga has also inundated some areas in Ekla and Yamuna Bazar of national capital Delhi. Ganga in Sambhal has risen above the danger mark and the rising water level of Ganga is giving tough time to the residents of Farruddinagar in Ghaziabad. Along with Ganga its tributaries are also flowing just near the danger marks. Uttar Pradesh chief minister Akhilesh Yadav has instructed the authorities concerned to make the arrangements to help the people who are affected by the rising water of Ganga. The situation in the national capital is very well under control according to Delhi's deputy chief minister Manish Sisodia's tweet in concerns with the rising water levels of Gang and the affected areas in Delhi. User can call at the number - 1077 for any emergency help related to flood.
